\[\text{Wasserstein Distance loss}=\inf_{\pi}\mathcal{L}_{ \mathcal{W}}(t)=||\mu_{t}-(A\mu_{t-1}+b)||_{2}^{2}+\] \[Tr\Bigg{(}A\Sigma_{t-1}A^{T}+\Sigma_{t}-2\big{(}\Sigma_{t}^{ \frac{1}{2}}A\Sigma_{t-1}A^{T}\Sigma_{t}^{\frac{1}{2}}\big{)}^{\frac{1}{2}} \Bigg{)}\]

Then, we can have

\[\inf_{\pi}\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{W}}(t) =||\mu_{t}-(A\mu_{t-1}+b)||_{2}^{2}+Tr\Bigg{(}A\Sigma_{t-1}A^{T}+ \Sigma_{t}\Bigg{)}-\Bigg{(}2Tr\big{(}\Sigma_{t}^{\frac{1}{2}}A\Sigma_{t-1}A^{T }\Sigma_{t}^{\frac{1}{2}}\big{)}^{\frac{1}{2}}\Bigg{)}\] \[=||\mu_{t}-(A\mu_{t-1}+b)||_{2}^{2}+Tr\Bigg{(}A\Sigma_{t-1}A^{T}+ \Sigma_{t}\Bigg{)}-\Bigg{(}2Tr\big{(}A^{T}\Sigma_{t}A\Sigma_{t-1}\big{)}^{ \frac{1}{2}}\Bigg{)}\] \[=||\mu_{t}-(A\mu_{t-1}+b)||_{2}^{2}+Tr\Bigg{(}A\Sigma_{t-1}A^{T}+ \Sigma_{t}-2\big{(}A^{T}\Sigma_{t}A\Sigma_{t-1}\big{)}^{\frac{1}{2}}\Bigg{)}\] \[=||\mu_{t}-(A\mu_{t-1}+b)||_{2}^{2}+Tr\Bigg{(}(A^{T}\Sigma_{t}A- \Sigma_{t-1})(A^{T}\Sigma_{t}A-\Sigma_{t-1})^{T}\Bigg{)}\] \[=||\mu_{t}-(A\mu_{t-1}+b)||_{2}^{2}+||A^{T}\Sigma_{t}A-\Sigma_{t- 1}||_{F}\]

where \(||\cdot||_{F}\) is Frobenius norm. \(\inf_{\pi}\mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{W}}(t)=0\), and the infimum is attained when

\[\left\{\begin{array}{l}A\mu_{t-1}+b=\mu_{t}\\ A^{T}\Sigma_{t-1}A=\Sigma_{t}\end{array}\right.,\forall\;t=\{2,\ldots,T\} \tag{35}\]

We are dealing with a system where the matrix \(A\) and \(b\) together comprise \(n\times(n+1)\) unknown variables. At each time step \(t\), the system is described by \(n\times n\) quadratic equations and \(n\) linear equations. Typically, these quadratic equations yield two possible sets of solutions. To refine our estimates and converge towards the optimal parameters \((A^{*},b^{*})\), employing a large number of time steps (\(t\gg 1\)) allows us to formulate an overdetermined system of equations.

